entry.title: Reland "[mojo] Fix multi-broker networks on Windows"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 458f376a8c94c6113a2c77f8d050c7338583d370



It was reverted due a test leaking pipes and triggering LSan.

The test no longer leaks pipes.



Original change's description:

> [mojo] Fix multi-broker networks on Windows

>

> Handle passing between a non-broker and a secondary broker in

> multi-broker networks was broken on Windows. This change fixes it.

>

> The fix is specifically for this scenario:

>

> - a broker X is connected to another broker Y

> - X has a handle to Y's process; but Y has no handle to X's

> - X is the broker for (+ has a process handle for) non-broker Z

> - Y and Z require an introduction

> - X gives Y a transport for Z, including Z's process handle

>

> The bug is that because Y doesn't have a process handle for X,

> it will ignore *all* process handles sent by X, including the

> process handle for Z. As a result neither Y nor Z will have

> the other's process handle, and at least one must have the

> other's process handle in order for other handles to be

> transmissible between them.

>

> The fix is simply to remove the unnecessary constraint, as it

> appears to provide no security value: it doesn't matter if Y

> has no process handle for X. It can still accept handles to

> other processes from X.

>

> Fixed: 1432382

entry.title: Track parent_clip_rect across frames in SurfaceAggregator.
entry.content:
This is for the feature AllowUndamagedNonrootRenderPassToSkip.



Introduce |parent_clip_rect| which is the intersection of ancestors'

|output_rect|, RenderPassDrawQuad rect, SurfaceDrawQuad rect and |clip

rect|. If |parent_clip_rect| changes from the previous frame, this

render pass cannot be skipped.



If a render pass is merged to its parent render pass in the previous

frame but is not merged in the current frame, it has to redraw with full

damage because there is no separate output buffer for this render pass

when it's merged.



Remove in_pixel_moving_filter_pass from

SurfaceAggregator::RenderPassNeedsFullDamage(). The damage rect of a

render pass with filters is calculated correctly in Prewalk. It doesn't

need to full damage.



This implementation of tracking render pass parent_clip_rect across

frames fixes the regressions in linux WPT tests when a skipped render pass is allow.

entry.title: Fixed "Some tabs are showing “x” and can be closed during selection"
entry.content:
The cause of the issue is that when `TabGridMode` is changed the GridCell's `state` property is changed only for the visible cells. However, in some cases `UICollectionView` dequeues and configures more cells than are currently visible on the screen. Thus, those cells are never got updated about the `TabGridMode` change.



The fix updates the cells' `state` property if needed before displaying them.

entry.title: Add NV12_MULTIPLANE support to CopyOutputNV12() for blit requests
entry.content:
This CL adds support for NV12_MULTIPLANE to CopyOutputNV12() in the case

where a blit request is present and we are waiting for GPU work to

complete (the only case in which requests with NV12_MULTIPLANE format

are currently generated). This mostly involves parameterizing over the

number of mailboxes that should be interacted with throughout the flow.

The true meat of the change is where we obtain both surfaces from the

single multiplanar SI representation rather than the per-plane

representations.



This CL does not yet add support for the case of creating surfaces or

for the case where CopyOutputNV12() is not waiting for GPU work to

complete, but rather CHECK()s that these cases do not yet use

NV12_MULTIPLANE. Adding support for these and then enabling them via

FrameSinkVideoCapturerImpl is followup work.

entry.content:

command buffers, this includes Resize() calls. WebXR code has still

code path for real GLSurface and needs Resize, but it was calling it

without check. This was resulting in allocating textures that no-one

used and now it causes failures in the command buffers.



This CL makes WebXR only call resize for SurfaceTexture code path.

entry.title: [Payments] More verbose developer error message for manifest downloads
entry.content:
Before this patch, whenever Chrome failed to download a payment

manifest, the PaymentRequest.show() JS API returned a generic error

message "Unable to download payment manifest ."



The generic error message did not explain the reason for the failure,

which made it difficult for web developers to debug what happened. For

example, the payment manifest downloader has a 1MB limit, but the

generic error message did not reveal to the web developer when that

limit was being hit.



This patch extends the error message to provide either HTTP or network

error message or code. For example:



Unable to download payment manifest .

ERR_INSUFFICIENT_RESOURCES (-12)



Unable to download payment manifest .

HTTP 404 Not Found.

entry.title: Reduce the cache pressure of the CSSProperty array.
entry.content:
CSSProperty was recently inadvertently increased from 16 to 24 bytes.

Fix that, and also get rid of the kPropertyClasses[] array; it burns

~6 kB of cache that we'd really like to have for everything else,

and is a meaningless indirection. Instead, put every single

CSS(Unresolved)Property instance into a tightly packed array,

through some union trickery, making it possible to just index directly

into it. (The vtable pointer is still an indirection, but we can't

do much about that unless we start making our own OOP system.)

This isn't strictly by the book (the casting of an union instance

to a common base class isn't blessed by the standard), but should be

fine in practice as long as we don't introduce multiple inheritance or

similar shenanigans.



Since we've now got everything in the same table (instead of having

some in a table and some in a switch/case), we can easily

get rid of all the different special cases; we no longer need

if tests for whether something is an alias, for kVariable, etc..



There are some issues with LTO inlining, necessitating a bit uglier

.h file than we'd like; I've filed a separate bug for that.

entry.content:
The DanglingPointerDetector is configured only when the test enters the

ContentMain function. See https://crbug.com/1400059



I would like to configure it no matter the kind of test. For this to

happen, we need to annotate every pre-existing dangling pointers.



This patch annotates the ones you can find by running targets depending

on the GoogleTest library.



Statistic:



This adds 1776 new DanglingUntriaged. Among them:

- 1288 are in unittests.

- 488 are in implementation.



To produce those numbers, I used the command:

```bash

git diff annotate-linux origin/main -- "*test*" | grep "DanglingUntriaged" | wc -l

```



This patch has been generated by:



1. Apply the "auto-annotator" patch:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4474553



2. Compile the compiler again:

```bash

./tools/clang/scripts/build.py

```



3. List and run all the targets. You can use a bash script like:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1AMMERcqy0eafFWopUCHYsIKIKEp3J8DFxqW9UIbzIHo



4. Concatenate output, filter by "Found dangling ptr", sort, remove

duplicate.



5. Apply the rewriter script from:

https://github.com/ArthurSonzogni/chrome-dangling-ptr-apply-edit



6. Revert the "auto-annotate" patch.



7. Apply `git cl format`

entry.title: Ink Overflow for CSS pseudo highlights.
entry.content:
CSS pseudo highlights may include applied text decorations,

such as underlines, that extend outside the text's visual rect.

This CL adds support for accurate ink overflow for custom

highlights and text fragments.



There are several changes required to achieve this:

- Move the highlight marker validation step from the paint lifecycle

phase to the compositing inputs phase, to run before overflow

is calculated and paint layer sizes are assigned.

- Add a method for requesting new frames when visual overflow

needs recalculation, similar to those for raster invalidation.

- Add a method to DocumentMarkerController to iterate over all

markers of a type applying a function to the markers. This is

used to store overflow status on the marker itself and to

record nodes with markers that have overflow.

- Add code in the HighlightRegistry to request invalidation when

custom highlights with visual overflow are added and removed.

- Add code to AnnotationAgentImpl to invalidate target-text markers,

with a test in TextFragmentHandlerTest.

- Add ink overflow calculation in the ink overflow code itself.

entry.title: [base][test] Add a `RunUntil(<predicate>)` utility
entry.content:
It's very common that a test has to wait until a certain condition is

fulfilled. Often, the test knows this is the case by installing an

observer or callback.



However, quite often the code under test doesn't have an observer or

callback to report it is done, since it doesn't need one. This makes

testing this code a challenge.



This CL adds a utility that can be used in these cases:



// Example usage

ChangeColorFieldAsyncTo(object_under_test, kRed);



ASSERT_TRUE(RunUntil(

base::BindLambdaForTesting([&](){

return object_under_test.Color() == kRed;

})));



// When we come here we are guaranteed that

// `object_under_test.Color()` is set to `kRed`.



This utility will poll periodically until the predicate returns `true`

(or until we hit a timeout).

entry.title: [scroll-animations] Respect fill behavior on compositor
entry.content:
Previously once an animation produced a value we would apply that

value unconditionally to all pending trees. However, scroll

driven animations should only apply their values when active.



When a cc animation goes inactive we currently don't know what the underlying properties used to be before they were animated and

need a commit from the main thread. We should track the original

property values in the future but for now this fixes the visual

bug with occasional commits.



To ensure that time based animations work as before they are

modified to implicitly fill in the playback direction so that

they hold their final value until the next commit.

entry.title: Remember password by default on KerberosAccounts policy
entry.content:
Replace the `remember_password` field in the KerberosAccounts policy

with a new field called `remember_password_from_policy`. The new field

defaults to true. This makes the policy field consistent with the

corresponding checkbox in "Kerberos Add Account" dialog, modified in:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4551086



The `remember_password` field has never been exposed in the Admin

Console, where the KerberosAccounts policy currently can only be set

to use the login password. In this use case, the value of this field is

irrelevant.



For more details about this planned change, see the "Additional Change"

session of go/kerberos-preconfig-dd. The corresponding feature is

planned to launch in M-116 (see launch/4210638).
